Crown'd by the Nation's
Roger Hoveden tells us, he was elected King by the whole English Nation; and the Saxon Annals observe, as Mr. Tyrrel notes, in his Days, all things succeeded prosperously, God giving him Peace as long as he liv'd, because he consulted the Good and Peace of his People; and there∣fore he had greater Honour in all Nations round him, as well as in his own, and by a peculiar Blessing from Above, he was so assisted, that Kings submitted themselve to him every where, without fighting.
Also the Manscript Author of the Life of St. Dunstan, relates he was elected by the Clergy, as well as Laity, over both Kingdoms. [Tyrrel's Gen. Hist. of Eng. Vol. 1. Lib. 6. Fol. 1, 2.] Suffrage and Applause;
